What is Method Reference ?

Method references in Java are a feature introduced in Java 8 that allow you to refer to
methods directly by their names using the :: operator. They are a shorthand for lambda
expressions that call a specific method, making your code more readable and concise.

Why Use Method References?

(i) Improved readability: Code is easier to understand.
(ii) Less boilerplate: You reuse existing methods instead of writing new lambdas.
(iii) Functional programming style: Works well with streams and collections.
(iv) Fewer errors: Reduces logical and typo mistakes.


Types of Method References

There are four main types:

1. Reference to a Static Method

You can refer to a static method using the class name.

Syntax:

ClassName::staticMethodName

Example:

names.forEach(System.out::println);

Here, System.out::println is a method reference to the static method println of
System.out.

2. Reference to an Instance Method of a Particular Object

You can refer to an instance method of a specific object.

Syntax:

objectName::instanceMethodName

Example:

Number_Comparator comparator = new Number_Comparator();
numbers.stream().sorted(comparator::compare).toList();

Here, comparator::compare refers to the compare method of the comparator object.

3. Reference to an Instance Method of an Arbitrary Object of a Particular Type

You can refer to an instance method of any object of a particular type.

Syntax:

ClassName::instanceMethodName

Example:

numbers.stream().sorted(Integer::compareTo).toList();

Here, Integer::compareTo refers to the compareTo method of any Integer object.

4. Reference to a Constructor

You can refer to a constructor using the new keyword.

Syntax:

ClassName::new

Example:

studentNames.stream().map(Student::new).toArray(Student[]::new);

Here, Student::new creates a new Student object for each name.


Summary Table

Type	                                    Syntax	                    Example

Static method	                            ClassName::methodName	    Math::abs
Instance method of a particular object	    object::methodName	        myList::size
Instance method of arbitrary object type	ClassName::methodName	  String::toLowerCase
Constructor	                                ClassName::new	            ArrayList::new


When to Use Method References?

When you have a lambda expression that only calls a method.
When working with streams and collections for operations like sorting, mapping, or
printing.


What is the advantage of method reference?

You don't have to create obj of that class , you can directly refer to that method .